I'm getting a 2016 e-Golf with the 7.7 Kw charger.  I got the JuiceBox Pro 40 with the NEMA 14-50 plug.  http://a.co/d/aNcrWzN  The EVSE is more than what I need but I am future proofing myself. I decided to go with the NEMA 14-50 instead of hard-wired so that I have flexibility and when my Tesla friends come visit, they can either use my EVSE or plug in directly to the NEMA 14-50. I have a 50 Amp circuit.

&amp;#x200B;

The Wi-Fi is nice because it allows you to see the charging sessions and energy that has been put in the car. It also allows you to share the same circuit with multiple EVSE so that if you end up adding a second one, they will know what each other is pumping out so that they don't overload the circuit.

They  make something like 22 000 a year or so?

That is something like the amount of Model 3s a month. Its a huge amount more units to spread fixed costs like development and factory space around. 

